<subSubSection id="90A86537FFE1FFE208595A58FBFB9A78" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="249" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" type="key">
<keyStep id="63462E19FFE1FFE508595A58FBDD9B7E" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE1FFE508595A58FBDD9B5E" blockId="19.[113,1089,1338,1618]" box="[113,1088,1338,1362]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE1FFE508595A58FBDD9B5E" box="[113,1088,1338,1362]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">1 Wing with membrane unicolorous; posterior cross-vein (dm-cu) absent. .................. 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE1FFE508595A38FBDD9B7E" blockId="19.[113,1089,1338,1618]" box="[113,1088,1370,1394]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE1FFE508595A38FBDD9B7E" box="[113,1088,1370,1394]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
– Wing with fumose cloudings; posterior cross-vein (dm-cu) developed (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE1FFE50B8A5A38FC799B7E" box="[930,996,1370,1394]" captionStart="Figs 1–2" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1521,1540]" captionTargetBox="[187,1094,222,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[187,1095,222,1470]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–2. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov. 1 – male holotype, body length ca 3.4 mm; 2 – wing, length 3.1 mm, male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378011/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). ....... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="63462E19FFE1FFE208595A18FBFB9F98" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="249" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE1FFE508595A18FBDD985E" blockId="19.[113,1089,1338,1618]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE1FFE508595A18FBDD985E" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
2(1) Larger species (body length more than 
<quantity id="1F4A9B59FFE1FFE50A7E5A18FD049B9E" box="[598,665,1402,1426]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
). Antennal pedicel (not scape) blackish brown. Ventral part of face yellow, whitish microtomentose and with 5–6 pairs of setae. Mesonotum grey microtomentose with a pair of longitudinal brownish microtomentose vittae. A pair of strong prescutellar ac setae (situated in front of posterior dc) present. Male genitalia with robust elongately triangular surstylus, short subtriangular gonostylus (
<bibRefCitation id="BC234B4DFFE1FFE509195978FDBE983E" author="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P." box="[305,547,1562,1586]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" pagination="345 - 371" refId="ref11950" refString="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P. 2011: A revision of the Palaearctic Periscelidinae with notes on some New World species (Diptera: Periscelididae). Annales Historico-Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici 103: 345 - 371." type="journal article" year="2011">PAPP &amp; WITHERS 2011</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE1FFE50A075978FDF0983E" box="[559,621,1562,1586]" captionStart="Figs 1–2" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1521,1540]" captionTargetBox="[187,1094,222,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[187,1095,222,1470]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–2. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov. 1 – male holotype, body length ca 3.4 mm; 2 – wing, length 3.1 mm, male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378011/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) and cercus large, broad and with long setae. ......................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="1FB24D3FFFE1FFE50B1D5958FBDD985E" authority="Loew, 1858" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1858" box="[821,1088,1593,1618]" class="Insecta" family="Periscelididae" genus="Periscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulipes">
<emphasis id="EAC6EAAEFFE1FFE50B1D5958FC21985D" bold="true" box="[821,956,1593,1617]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">P. annulipes</emphasis>
Loew, 1858
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE6FFE208BF5FBEFBFB9F98" blockId="20.[151,1127,219,1140]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE6FFE208BF5FBEFBFB9F98" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
– Smaller species (body length distinctly less than 
<quantity id="1F4A9B59FFE6FFE20AF25FBEFC819EF8" box="[730,796,220,244]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
). Pedicel pale brown, ochreous yellow basally. Ventral part of face brown, grey microtomentose and with only 1 pair of setae. Mesonotum dark grey, with pale grey microtomentum. No prescutellar ac. Male genitalia with very slender and long surstylus, elongately subtriangular gonostylus, and cercus more slender but with robust setae (
<bibRefCitation id="BC234B4DFFE6FFE20AD55E3EFC709F78" author="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P." box="[765,1005,348,372]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249" pagination="345 - 371" refId="ref11950" refString="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P. 2011: A revision of the Palaearctic Periscelidinae with notes on some New World species (Diptera: Periscelididae). Annales Historico-Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici 103: 345 - 371." type="journal article" year="2011">PAPP &amp; WITHERS 2011</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20BD05E39FBC79F78" box="[1016,1114,347,372]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1450,1469]" captionTargetBox="[152,1122,222,1367]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[149,1130,216,1397]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 6–10. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). 6 – entire genitalia, laterally; 7 – surstylus, laterally; 8 – postgonite, laterally; 9 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 10 – cercus, laterally.Scale = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378015/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Figs 6, 7</figureCitation>
). ..................................................................................................................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="63462E19FFE6FFE208BF5EFEFBFB9C58" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE6FFE208BF5EFEFBFB9FFF" blockId="20.[151,1127,219,1140]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE6FFE208BF5EFEFBFB9FFF" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
3(2) Gonostylus longer, hence surstylus less than 1.4 times as long as gonostylus (
<bibRefCitation id="BC234B4DFFE6FFE20C305EFEFEF19FD8" author="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P." pageId="20" pageNumber="249" pagination="345 - 371" refId="ref11950" refString="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P. 2011: A revision of the Palaearctic Periscelidinae with notes on some New World species (Diptera: Periscelididae). Annales Historico-Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici 103: 345 - 371." type="journal article" year="2011">PAPP &amp; WITHERS 2011</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE2095E5ED9FE2B9FDF" box="[374,438,443,467]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); ejacapodeme more robust and proximally not widened (
<bibRefCitation id="BC234B4DFFE6FFE20C315EDEFEF09FF8" author="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P." pageId="20" pageNumber="249" pagination="345 - 371" refId="ref11950" refString="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P. 2011: A revision of the Palaearctic Periscelidinae with notes on some New World species (Diptera: Periscelididae). Annales Historico-Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici 103: 345 - 371." type="journal article" year="2011">PAPP &amp; WITHERS 2011</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE2095F5EB9FE269FF8" box="[375,443,475,500]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209EF5EB9FE4A9FFF" box="[455,471,475,499]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1450,1469]" captionTargetBox="[152,1122,222,1367]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[149,1130,216,1397]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 6–10. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). 6 – entire genitalia, laterally; 7 – surstylus, laterally; 8 – postgonite, laterally; 9 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 10 – cercus, laterally.Scale = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378015/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">6</figureCitation>
). ........................................ 
<taxonomicName id="1FB24D3FFFE6FFE20B295EBEFBFB9FFF" authority="nigra (Zetterstedt, 1860)" authorityName="nigra (Zetterstedt" authorityYear="1860" baseAuthorityName="Zetterstedt" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[769,1126,475,499]" class="Insecta" family="Periscelididae" genus="Periscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="nigra" subSpecies="nigra">
<emphasis id="EAC6EAAEFFE6FFE20B295EBEFC049FFF" bold="true" box="[769,921,475,499]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">P. nigra nigra</emphasis>
(Zetterstedt, 1860)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE6FFE208BF5E9EFBFB9C58" blockId="20.[151,1127,219,1140]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE6FFE208BF5E9EFBFB9C58" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
– Gonostylus shorter, hence surstylus about 1.6 times as long as gonostylus (
<bibRefCitation id="BC234B4DFFE6FFE20C3D5E9EFEF19C38" author="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P." pageId="20" pageNumber="249" pagination="345 - 371" refId="ref11950" refString="PAPP L. &amp; WITHERS P. 2011: A revision of the Palaearctic Periscelidinae with notes on some New World species (Diptera: Periscelididae). Annales Historico-Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici 103: 345 - 371." type="journal article" year="2011">PAPP &amp; WITHERS 2011</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE2095D5D79FE2A9C3F" box="[373,439,539,563]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1450,1469]" captionTargetBox="[152,1122,222,1367]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[149,1130,216,1397]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 6–10. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). 6 – entire genitalia, laterally; 7 – surstylus, laterally; 8 – postgonite, laterally; 9 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 10 – cercus, laterally.Scale = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378015/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Figs 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209EA5D7EFE429C38" box="[450,479,540,564]" captionStart="Figs 11–14" captionStartId="13.[113,150,1512,1531]" captionTargetBox="[118,1081,425,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-13@13.[111,1092,415,1503]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 11–14. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). 11 – external genitalia caudally (surstyli omitted); 12 – same, cranially (cerci omitted); 13 – pregenital sternum (S6), ventrally; 14 – aedeagal complex, laterally (only basal part of distiphallus depicted). Scale = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378017/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209C05D79FD989C3F" box="[488,517,539,563]" captionStart="Figs 15–21" captionStartId="14.[151,188,1488,1507]" captionTargetBox="[158,1125,385,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-10@14.[149,1130,375,1478]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 15–21.Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., female paratype (Portugal:Valongo). 15 – postabdomen, dorsally; 16 – T8, dorsally; 17 – S8, ventrally; 18 – spermathecae; 19 – ventral receptacle, laterally; 20 – 5th segment and postabdomen, ventrally; 21 – posterior part of postabdomen (from 7th segment), laterally. Scales = 0.2 mm (Figs 15, 20, 21) and 0.1 mm (Figs 16–19). For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378019/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">15</figureCitation>
); ejacapodeme more slender and proximally dilated (
