<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE6FFE208BF5D3EFBFB9D7F" blockId="20.[151,1127,219,1140]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE6FFE208BF5D3EFBFB9D7F" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
4(3) Antennal pedicel with blackish spot on outer side extended laterally up to ventral margin (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209075D19FEEC9C9F" box="[303,369,635,659]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum medially unicolorous grey (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20B105D19FCE49C9F" box="[824,889,635,659]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) or with brown vittae only indicated (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209555DF9FE539CB8" box="[381,462,667,692]" captionStart="Figs 33–34" captionStartId="18.[151,188,1297,1316]" captionTargetBox="[189,1089,219,1287]" captionTargetId="figure-10@18.[189,1089,219,1287]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 33–34. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, female (Slovakia), body length ca 4.2 mm. 33 – living adult, laterally; 34 – same specimen, dorsally. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378025/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
); scutellum all dark or with yellow restricted to apex (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20C335DF9FBFF9CBF" box="[1051,1122,667,691]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Figs 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE208FC5DDEFF6F9CD8" box="[212,242,700,724]" captionStart="Figs 33–34" captionStartId="18.[151,188,1297,1316]" captionTargetBox="[189,1089,219,1287]" captionTargetId="figure-10@18.[189,1089,219,1287]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 33–34. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, female (Slovakia), body length ca 4.2 mm. 33 – living adult, laterally; 34 – same specimen, dorsally. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378025/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">34</figureCitation>
). Male S6 widened posteriorly, brown pigmented along anterior and lateral margins, simple posteromedially (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20A335DB9FDF19CF8" box="[539,620,731,756]" captionStart="Figs 22–27" captionStartId="16.[150,187,903,922]" captionTargetBox="[179,1105,222,879]" captionTargetId="figure-239@16.[151,1126,216,887]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 22–27. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male (Hungary). 22 – pregenital sternum (S6), ventrally; 23 – ejacapodeme, laterally; 24 – surstylus, laterally; 25 – postgonite, laterally; 26 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 27 – cercus, laterally. Scales = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378021" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378021/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Gonostylus more slender and with apex bent anteriorly (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209615D99FE049D1F" box="[329,409,763,787]" captionStart="Figs 22–27" captionStartId="16.[150,187,903,922]" captionTargetBox="[179,1105,222,879]" captionTargetId="figure-239@16.[151,1126,216,887]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 22–27. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male (Hungary). 22 – pregenital sternum (S6), ventrally; 23 – ejacapodeme, laterally; 24 – surstylus, laterally; 25 – postgonite, laterally; 26 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 27 – cercus, laterally. Scales = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378021" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378021/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
); postgonite distally more robust but its broad proximal part not extended posteroventrally (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209F65C79FDB29D3F" box="[478,559,795,819]" captionStart="Figs 22–27" captionStartId="16.[150,187,903,922]" captionTargetBox="[179,1105,222,879]" captionTargetId="figure-239@16.[151,1126,216,887]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 22–27. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male (Hungary). 22 – pregenital sternum (S6), ventrally; 23 – ejacapodeme, laterally; 24 – surstylus, laterally; 25 – postgonite, laterally; 26 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 27 – cercus, laterally. Scales = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378021" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378021/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). Female T8 posteromedially pale-pigmented, darker only laterally (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209475C59FE229D58" box="[367,447,827,852]" captionStart="Figs 28–32" captionStartId="17.[113,150,1119,1138]" captionTargetBox="[139,1070,213,1091]" captionTargetId="figure-13@17.[113,1088,196,1107]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 28–32. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, female (Hungary).28 – 5th segment and postabdomen, ventrally; 29 – T8, dorsally; 30 – S8, ventrally; 31– ventral receptacle, laterally; 32 – spermathecae. Scales = 0.2 mm (Fig. 28) and 0.1 mm (Figs 29–32). For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378023" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378023/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
); S8 narrowly brown only laterally and less densely setose (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20C135C59FF6F9D78" captionStart="Figs 28–32" captionStartId="17.[113,150,1119,1138]" captionTargetBox="[139,1070,213,1091]" captionTargetId="figure-13@17.[113,1088,196,1107]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 28–32. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, female (Hungary).28 – 5th segment and postabdomen, ventrally; 29 – T8, dorsally; 30 – S8, ventrally; 31– ventral receptacle, laterally; 32 – spermathecae. Scales = 0.2 mm (Fig. 28) and 0.1 mm (Figs 29–32). For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378023" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378023/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). ........................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="1FB24D3FFFE6FFE20B7E5C3EFBFB9D7F" authority="Egger, 1862" authorityName="Egger" authorityYear="1862" box="[854,1126,859,884]" class="Insecta" family="Periscelididae" genus="Periscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="winnertzii">
<emphasis id="EAC6EAAEFFE6FFE20B7E5C3EFC439D7F" bold="true" box="[854,990,859,883]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">P. winnertzii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="BC234B4DFFE6FFE20BCD5C3EFBFB9D7F" author="EGGER J." box="[997,1126,859,884]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249" pagination="777 - 784" refId="ref11326" refString="EGGER J. 1862: Dipterologische Beitrage. Fortsetzung der Beschreibungen neuer Dipteren. Verhandlungen der Zoologisch-Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien 12: 777 - 784." type="journal article" year="1862">Egger, 1862</bibRefCitation>
