</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D80D36BCFFE6FFE208BF5C1EFBFB9A78" blockId="20.[151,1127,219,1140]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
<keyLead id="63439589FFE6FFE208BF5C1EFBFB9A78" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
– Antennal pedicel with blackish spot smaller, laterally reaching to about half of its outer side (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209245CF9FED19DB8" box="[268,332,923,948]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum medially with distinct pair of brown vittae (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20B835CF9FC769DB8" box="[939,1003,923,948]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); scutellum with largely or entirely yellow disc (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20A485CD9FD3F9DD8" box="[608,674,955,980]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Male S6 suboblong, not widened posteriorly, brown pigmented only laterally and with narrow medial depression (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20C215CB9FBC49DF8" box="[1033,1113,987,1012]" captionStart="Figs 11–14" captionStartId="13.[113,150,1512,1531]" captionTargetBox="[118,1081,425,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-13@13.[111,1092,415,1503]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 11–14. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). 11 – external genitalia caudally (surstyli omitted); 12 – same, cranially (cerci omitted); 13 – pregenital sternum (S6), ventrally; 14 – aedeagal complex, laterally (only basal part of distiphallus depicted). Scale = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378017/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Gonostylus shorter and thicker, with apex simple (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20B2A5C99FCDB9A18" box="[770,838,1019,1044]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1450,1469]" captionTargetBox="[152,1122,222,1367]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[149,1130,216,1397]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 6–10. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). 6 – entire genitalia, laterally; 7 – surstylus, laterally; 8 – postgonite, laterally; 9 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 10 – cercus, laterally.Scale = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378015/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); postgonite distally more slender and broad proximal part produced posteroventrally (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20B7C5B79FC089A38" box="[852,917,1051,1076]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1450,1469]" captionTargetBox="[152,1122,222,1367]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[149,1130,216,1397]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 6–10. Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype (Portugal: Valongo). 6 – entire genitalia, laterally; 7 – surstylus, laterally; 8 – postgonite, laterally; 9 – gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension); 10 – cercus, laterally.Scale = 0.1 mm. For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378015/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
, arrow). Female T8 uniformly brown pigmented (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE20A245B59FDC49A5F" box="[524,601,1083,1107]" captionStart="Figs 15–21" captionStartId="14.[151,188,1488,1507]" captionTargetBox="[158,1125,385,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-10@14.[149,1130,375,1478]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 15–21.Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., female paratype (Portugal:Valongo). 15 – postabdomen, dorsally; 16 – T8, dorsally; 17 – S8, ventrally; 18 – spermathecae; 19 – ventral receptacle, laterally; 20 – 5th segment and postabdomen, ventrally; 21 – posterior part of postabdomen (from 7th segment), laterally. Scales = 0.2 mm (Figs 15, 20, 21) and 0.1 mm (Figs 16–19). For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378019/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
); S8 narrowly brown laterally and posteriorly and more densely setose (
<figureCitation id="40892A39FFE6FFE209915B39FD959A78" box="[441,520,1115,1140]" captionStart="Figs 15–21" captionStartId="14.[151,188,1488,1507]" captionTargetBox="[158,1125,385,1457]" captionTargetId="figure-10@14.[149,1130,375,1478]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 15–21.Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., female paratype (Portugal:Valongo). 15 – postabdomen, dorsally; 16 – T8, dorsally; 17 – S8, ventrally; 18 – spermathecae; 19 – ventral receptacle, laterally; 20 – 5th segment and postabdomen, ventrally; 21 – posterior part of postabdomen (from 7th segment), laterally. Scales = 0.2 mm (Figs 15, 20, 21) and 0.1 mm (Figs 16–19). For abbreviations see p. 231." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378019/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). ........................................................... 
